      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Fry the chorizo and build the base",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the olive oil in a large saucepan over medium heat. Add the chorizo and cook for 3 to 4 minutes until browned and the red-orange fat has rendered into the pan. Add the onion and cook for 8 minutes until soft. Add the garlic and smoked paprika, stir for 1 minute. Add the tinned tomatoes and cook for 5 minutes, breaking up the tomatoes with a spoon.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Add the beans and simmer",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Add the butter beans, stock, and bay leaves. Bring to a simmer and cook for 15 to 20 minutes until the broth has thickened slightly and the beans are fully tender. Crush a few beans against the side of the pan to help thicken the broth. Remove the bay leaves, season, and scatter with parsley. Serve with crusty bread.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Crush more beans against the pan wall; simmer uncovered for a further 10 minutes",
              "cause": "Not enough simmering time or beans not crushed",
              "symptom": "Broth is thin"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Use low-sodium stock and don't add salt until you have tasted the finished dish",
              "cause": "Chorizo is already quite salty; combined with stock the salt builds",
              "symptom": "Stew is too salty"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Spanish bean stews are winter food and weekend food, something that simmers on the back of the hob while the household does other things. The famous Asturian fabada uses fabes (large local white beans) and morcilla as well as chorizo, but this version, made with tinned butter beans and a single cut of chorizo, gives almost the same result in a fraction of the time. The key is the smoked paprika: it carries the whole flavour of the dish.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
